# Scatter Plot to show coorelation between Volume & Turnover for various stocks in Nifty 50 over the years.

n = d["Symbol"].nunique()
s = d["Symbol"].unique()

for i in range(0,n):
    plt.subplots(1,1)
    plt.scatter(d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["Volume"].sum()/1000,d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["Turnover"].sum()/100000)
    plt.title(s[i])
    plt.xlabel("Volume in 1,000s")
    plt.ylabel("Turnover in 1,00,000s")
    plt.show()

As most of the plots are making a straight line with 45 angle, so volume & turnover have a positive coorelation near to 1. To support the above statement below is the coorelation plot for the same.

In [ ]:
n = d["Symbol"].nunique()
s = d["Symbol"].unique()

for i in range(0,n):
    p = d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["Volume"].sum()/1000
    a = d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["Turnover"].sum()/100000
    print(s[i])
    plt.subplots(1,1)
    sns.heatmap((pd.merge(p,a,right_index = True,left_index = True)).corr())
    plt.show()

# Scatter Plot to show the effect of difference in opening price on the high of that day for various stocks in Nifty 50 over the years.

n = d["Symbol"].nunique()
s = d["Symbol"].unique()

for i in range(0,n):
    plt.subplots(1,1)
    plt.scatter(d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["Dif"].sum(),d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["High"].sum())
    plt.title(s[i])
    plt.xlabel("Opening diff")
    plt.ylabel("High")
    plt.show()

To study the above grapths we have to ignore the plots where difference is near to zero.

Also, here correlation plot will fail to show any result.

So, in below plots the difference of 10% or less is deleted & then plotting is done.

d2 = pd.read_excel(r'D:\Dipesh\CU\Winning Camp\EDA Project\Datasets\NIFTY50_effect_of_opening_dif.xlsx')

n = d2["Symbol"].nunique()
s = d2["Symbol"].unique()

for i in range(0,n):
    plt.subplots(1,1)
    plt.scatter(d2[d2["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["Diff"].sum(),d[d["Symbol"]==s[i]].groupby("Date")["High"].sum())
    plt.title(s[i])
    plt.xlabel("Opening diff")
    plt.ylabel("High")
